Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Trim the @aubergine{1}, then cut into roughly 3cm pieces.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}). Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}.

Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks and all).

Pop the aubergine onto a large #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{}, then season with @salt{}, @pepper{} and the @curry powder{1%mix}. Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until the aubergine is soft and golden, ~{20-25%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

While the aubergine roasts, heat a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @desiccated coconut{25%g} and cook, stirring regularly, until lightly toasted, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> Watch it like a hawk as it can burn easily.

Once toasted, transfer to a #bowl{}.

Pop the (now empty) frying pan back on medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}.

Once hot, add the @rogan josh curry paste{50%g} and half the garlic. Stir and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @chopped tomatoes{1}(with onion and garlic), @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, chickpeas, @sugar{1/2%tsp} and @water{50%ml} for the curry (see pantry for both amounts). Simmer, stirring occasionally, until thickened, ~{10-15%minutes}.

When the curry is almost ready, pop the @plain naans{2} on a baking tray.

Drizzle with @oil{} and scatter over the remaining garlic and a quarter of the coriander. Pop them into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir the roasted aubergine and remaining coriander into the curry. Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed.

When ready, serve the aubergine curry in #bowls{}.

Top with a dollop of @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g} and a sprinkle of desiccated coconut.

Serve the naan breads alongside for dipping and scooping.

Enjoy!